aws-transcripts.transcript: This is a photograph of a man whom for many years I plotted to kill. This is my father, Clinton George Bag I Grant. It's called bad Guy because he has permanent bags under his eyes. As a 10 year old, along with my siblings, I dreamt off, scraping off the poison from fly killer paper into his coffee, grounded down glass and sprinkling it over his breakfast, loosening the carpet on the stairs so he would trip and break his neck. Become the day he'd always skipped that loose step. It was bound out of the house without so much of a swig of coffee or a bite to eat. So for many years I fear that my father would die before I had a chance to kill him up until our mother asked him to leave and not come back. Bag. I had been a terrifying ogre. Hey, Teach did permanent on the verge of rage rather like me. Ah, he worked nights at Boxall Motors in loosen and demanded total silence throughout the house so that when we came home from school at 3 30 in the afternoon would huddle beside the TV and other like safe crackers with twiddle with the volume control knob on the TV, said That was almost inaudible. And at times when we were like this, there's so much going on in the house. I imagine this to be like thee German crew of a U boat creeping along the edge of the ocean whilst up above on the surface. Hate Miss Bagai patrols, ready to drop depth charges at the first sound of any disturbance. So that lesson was a lesson that do not draw attention to yourself, either in the home or outside of the home. Maybe it's a migrant lesson. We were to be below the radar, so there was no communication, really between bad guy at us and us and bad guy and the sound that we most look forward to. You know, when you're a child and you want your father to come home and we're gonna be happy and waiting for that sound of the door opening. Well, the sound that we look forward to was the click off the door Closing, which meant he'd gone on, would not come back. So for three decades, I never laid eyes on my father, nor he on me We never spoke to each other for three decades, and then a couple of years ago, I decided to turn the spotlight on him.
